### 🚀 The feature, motivation and pitch

Currently, vLLM's support for FP8 KV Cache only allows a global uniform format (e.g., full e4m3 or e5m2). However, in practice, different model layers exhibit significant variations in sensitivity to quantization precision. For example, middle layers of Llama-3 may be more sensitive to precision loss with e4m3, while early layers may better suit e5m2's dynamic range.

This feature proposes to support mixed-precision KV Cache, including:

1. Allowing users to specify layer-wise format policies via configuration files (e.g., JSON/YAML) such as `layer 0-10: e5m2, layer 11-30: e4m3`;
2. Framework-automatic identification of critical layers (via quantization sensitivity analysis, e.g., layers with high impact on output logits) and assigning higher-precision formats (e.g., e4m3) to them, while using e5m2 for non-critical layers;
3. Resolving attention computation compatibility under mixed formats, such as unifying precision before matrix multiplication or leveraging hardware-native FP8 conversion units (e.g., Hopper) to accelerate cross-format calculations.

The core value of this feature is to further reduce precision loss while maintaining high throughput, especially for long-context scenarios and output-quality-sensitive tasks (e.g., code generation, medical text parsing).

### Alternatives

1. Global e4m3 format: Ensures precision but may cause numerical overflow in some layers due to limited dynamic range;
2. Global e5m2 format: Avoids overflow but sacrifices precision in critical layers;
3. Manual adjustment of model layer structures to fit a single format: High cost and poor generality.


### Additional context

1. Implementation must consider compatibility with existing KV Cache management logic (e.g., PagedAttention), especially memory block allocation under layer-wise formats;
2. Can be integrated with LLM Compressor's calibration tools to generate layer-specific scaling factors, further improving precision;

